  "prompt": "Is it true that most of the people who won the lottery eventually filed for bankruptcy?",
  "response": "The claim that most lottery winners eventually file for bankruptcy is a bit of an exaggeration. While there are notable stories of lottery winners who have encountered financial difficulties and even filed for bankruptcy, these instances do not represent the majority of lottery winners.\n\nResearch on the subject, such as a study conducted by the National Endowment for Financial Education, suggests that about 70% of lottery winners end up spending all their winnings within a few years. However, filing for bankruptcy is a more severe outcome and is not as common as the general financial struggle and mismanagement that some winners experience.\n\nThe tendency for some lottery winners to encounter financial troubles can often be attributed to a lack of proper financial planning and management, sudden changes in lifestyle, or the pressures of newfound wealth. It's important to highlight that with the right guidance and responsible financial management, many lottery winners are able to maintain and grow their wealth successfully.",
